"Ivanochko T.S., Ganeshram R.S., Brummer G.-J.A., Ganssen G., Jung S.J.A., Moreton S.G., Kroon D.","Variations in tropical convection as an amplifier of global climate change at the millennial scale",2005,"Earth and Planetary Science Letters","235","1-2",,"302","314",,,10.1016/j.epsl.2005.04.002,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-20544470386&partnerID=40&md5=b04360447c9d34fb27121094631ee82c","School of GeoSciences, Grant Institute, University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh EH9 3JW, United Kingdom; Dept. Marine Chemistry and Geology, Royal Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, Texel, Netherlands; Institute of Earth Sciences, Free University, Amsterdam, Netherlands; NERC Radiocarbon Laboratory, East Kilbride, United Kingdom; Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, 6339 Stores Road, Vancour, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada","Ivanochko, T.S., School of GeoSciences, Grant Institute, University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh EH9 3JW, United Kingdom, Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, 6339 Stores Road, Vancour, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada; Ganeshram, R.S., School of GeoSciences, Grant Institute, University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh EH9 3JW, United Kingdom; Brummer, G.-J.A., Dept. Marine Chemistry and Geology, Royal Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, Texel, Netherlands; Ganssen, G., Institute of Earth Sciences, Free University, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Jung, S.J.A., Institute of Earth Sciences, Free University, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Moreton, S.G., NERC Radiocarbon Laboratory, East Kilbride, United Kingdom; Kroon, D., Institute of Earth Sciences, Free University, Amsterdam, Netherlands","The global expression of millennial-scale climatic change during the glacial period and the persistence of this signal in Holocene records point to atmospheric teleconnections as the mechanism propagating rapid climate variations. We suggest rearrangements in the tropical convection system globally affected the concentration and location of atmospheric water vapour and modulated terrestrial and marine emissions of CH4 and N2O, providing a tropical mechanism of amplifying and perpetuating millennial-scale climate changes. A multi-proxy reconstruction reflecting various aspects of the intensity of the Arabian Sea Summer Monsoon shows strong millennial-scale variability over the past 90 kyr in which low intensity is associated with a southern shift of the Intertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ) and an eastward shift in the equatorial convergence zone. The monsoon reconstruction, which is based on new data from a Somali margin sediment core, is supported by previously reported tropical paleoclimatic records and suggests that global scale millennial climatic variability is in part driven by modulations in the tropical hydrological cycle and tropical emissions of the greenhouse gases CH4 and N2O. © 2005 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Aridity; Denitrification; Dust; Intertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ); Marine productivity; Millennial-scale oscillations; Monsoon; Rapid climate change; Tropical convection","Greenhouse gases; Marine emissions; Monsoon reconstruction; Sediment cores; Glacial geology; Greenhouse effect; Heat convection; Hydrology; Sediments; Vapors; Climate change; atmospheric convection; climate change",,,,,,"Wang, L., Sarnthein, M., Grootes, P., Erlenkeuser, H., Millennial reoccurrence of century-scale abrupt events of East Asian Monsoon: A possible heat conveyor for the global deglaciation (1999) Paleoceanography, 14 (6), pp. 725-731; Nair, R.R., Ittekkot, V., Manganini, S.J., Ramaswamy, V., Haake, B., Degens, E.T., Desai, B.N., Honjo, S., Increased particle flux to the deep ocean related to monsoons (1989) Nature, 338, pp. 749-751; Clemens, S.C., Prell, W.L., Late Pleistocene variability of Arabian Sea summer monsoon winds and continental aridity: Eolian records from the lithogenic components of deep sea sediments (1990) Paleoceanography, 5 (2), pp. 109-145; Clemens, S.C., Dust resp